---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

// Future community-contributed sister site; swap in the real URL when it exists.
const COMMUNITY_SITE_URL = '#';
---

<Base
  title="How verification works — PWA Finder"
  description="What the Verified publisher badge on PWA Finder means and how listings earn it."
>
  <article class="detail">
    <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to home</a>
    <h1>How verification works</h1>
    <p>
      Every listing with a <span class="verified-badge">✔ Verified</span> badge
      has passed the checks below. The badge doesn't certify that an app is
      good or bug-free — it certifies that the listing points to
      the{' '}<em>genuine publisher's</em> app, not an imitation.
    </p>

    <div class="install-help">
      <h2>1. Official URL, not a lookalike</h2>
      <p>
        The listing links to the publisher's canonical domain (for
        example{' '}<code>photopea.com</code>), served over HTTPS. The browser's
        certificate system proves the site is controlled by whoever owns that
        domain, so our job is confirming it's the <em>right</em> domain — not
        a clone like <code>photopea-editor.app</code>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="install-help">
      <h2>2. Cross-referenced against authoritative sources</h2>
      <p>
        We confirm the domain is the one the publisher's own official
        channels point to — their company site, official documentation, or
        source-code repository. A lookalike domain can copy an app's design,
        but it can't make the publisher's real channels link to it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="install-help">
      <h2>3. Re-checked monthly</h2>
      <p>
        Domains can be sold, abandoned, or compromised after a listing is
        added, so verified listings are re-checked every month. If a listing
        stops passing the checks above, the badge is removed until it passes
        again.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="at-your-own-risk" style="margin-top:2rem;">
      Apps without the badge
    </h2>
    <p>
      Listings marked <span class="risk-badge">⚠ At your own risk</span> have
      not passed the checks above. That doesn't necessarily mean something is
      wrong — this group includes apps that are <em>difficult to verify</em>:
      some hide everything behind a sign-in page (Gmail, Outlook), some block
      automated checks entirely (WhatsApp, Canva), and some only load their
      app manifest through scripts our checker can't run (Instagram, Bluesky).
      We simply can't machine-confirm them, so we don't badge them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Unbadged listings will also come from our companion community
      directory, where anyone can contribute a PWA
      —{' '}<a href={COMMUNITY_SITE_URL}>browse the community directory</a>{' '}
      <em>(coming soon)</em>. Either way, treat unbadged apps as you would any
      unknown website: check the address bar before signing in or granting
      permissions.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
